+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Ek2ZyR9xfdxKtZ5CDihQmW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Working through design decisions in autopilot:\n\n**Q1: Architecture pattern?**\n→ Choosing: Layered architecture with clear separation (database layer → service layer → routes/websocket handlers)\nReasoning: The project is small enough that this keeps things simple while testable. No need for domain-driven or hexagonal patterns.\n\n**Q2: OT vs CRDT for conflict resolution?**\n→ Choosing: Operational Transform (OT) with server-authoritative model\nReasoning: OT is simpler to implement for a single-server setup. The server maintains the canonical version, transforms incoming operations against concurrent ones, and broadcasts. CRDTs are more complex and suited for peer-to-peer/offline scenarios we don't need.\n\n**Q3: OT operation model?**\n→ Choosing: Simple insert/delete operations with position-based transforms\nReasoning: Two operation types - `insert(position, text)` and `delete(position, count)`. Transform functions handle all 4 combinations (insert-vs-insert, insert-vs-delete, delete-vs-insert, delete-vs-delete). Each operation carries a `version` field so the server knows what document state it was based on.\n\n**Q4: WebSocket message protocol?**\n→ Choosing: JSON messages with type discriminator\nReasoning: Messages have a `type` field: `sync` (server→client on connect), `operation` (client→server edit), `broadcast` (server→client edit from another user), `ack` (server→client confirming operation), `error` (server→client). Simple and debuggable.\n\n**Q5: WebSocket connection path?**\n→ Choosing: `/docs/:id/ws` path pattern\nReasoning: Aligns with REST resource paths. The document ID in the URL lets the server route connections to the right document room.\n\n**Q6: Version tracking strategy?**\n→ Choosing: Monotonically increasing integer version per document, stored in versions table\nReasoning: Each operation increments the document version. Client operations include the version they were based on. Server transforms operations against all operations between the client's version and current version.\n\n**Q7: File structure?**\n→ Choosing: Flat module structure in src/\nReasoning: `server.ts` (entry + createApp), `database.ts` (SQLite wrapper), `routes.ts` (REST API), `websocket.ts` (WS handler), `ot.ts` (OT engine), `types.ts` (shared types). Small enough project that deeper nesting adds no value.\n\n**Q8: Document ID generation?**\n→ Choosing: crypto.randomUUID()\nReasoning: Built into Node.js, no extra dependencies. UUIDs are the standard for distributed-friendly IDs."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":262,"cache_read_input_tokens":24782,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":262},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d2897688-e6bb-4a62-94c8-e0f26f54d2bf","uuid":"00460681-b3a9-4084-b7ac-072539159dd7"}
